AB  - Fisheries in small island developing states (SIDS) are governed and operated in ways that may either complement, or compete and conflict with, other coastal and marine uses and users. Environmentally oriented interventions by non-governmental organizations (NGOs) impact upon fisheries harvest, post-harvest and supporting activities from policy to practical levels. Environmental actors, interests and issues may either enable or constrain fisheries in SIDS. Environmental interventions are of increasing importance as ecosystem approaches, climate change, depletion of major fish stocks and sustainable development occupy global centre stage. The complex interactions associated with these interventions are poorly documented and understood, however. This chapter examines the concepts, interactions, outcomes and lessons related to the environmental interventions by NGOs in the fisheries of Caribbean and Pacific SIDS. We highlight the synergies, solutions, challenges and constraints. From a governance perspective we suggest how NGO interventions may enhance the benefits derived mainly from small-scale fisheries in SIDS.
